12/30/17, 4:03 PM - David Lee: pasty (comparative pastier, superlative pastiest)

Like paste, sticky.
These mashed potatoes aren’t cooked well, they are very pasty.
pale, lacking colour, having a pallor
He is pasty-faced.
(figuratively) He was feeling pasty.
Are you feeling OK? You look a bit pasty.

            temp = numbers[i];
            numbers[i] = numbers[j];
            numbers[j] = temp;

}

2/26/18, 10:39 AM - Julia Kang: The teams are spanned across different products, imagine the following matrix:
 
                Sales and Business Development             Client Services                   Product                Service Delivery
CTLA                     
DCC
GC
FS
 
So we have CTLA product, CTLA Sales, GC Sales, GC client services etc…..
In general, Sales are more focus on new business with new client / existing client, they do sales pitch and relationship building etc… Client services are daily contact point for clients, mainly to ‘defend’ existing business. Product improves the existing product offering / launch new product due to regulatory changes or client demand. Service delivery is the team who actually do the jobs, which means operation.

3/28/18, 1:38 PM - Julia Kang: I was 9 when my little sister was born. Because I had been an only child for so long, I was not happy of how my parents were more concerned about the new born baby than me. I would often call her ugly for a while and told her that it meant ‘cute.’Now I have another sister, 13 years younger than me. The big age gap between us basically makes me feel like a mother of two daughters. Now that my parents are aging, I am slowly taking over their roles and responsibilities as a guardian and take them out to trips and make sure they are okay. We make sure to give each other gifts every time I go back home, and call very often. I am quite surprised that we have such relationship. Back when I used to live with them, I thought they were just annoying siblings who were too young to understand me. Now, they are such a big part of me that I even want to find a job in Korea just to spend more time with them.

Yeah, I have two sisters, with big age gaps of  9 and 13 years. 

I wasn’t a big family person. Only after coming to Hong Kong, I realised how much my sisters meant to me. I think it was the same for them too. We’ve developed stronger bond from the distance from each other. We call each other every other day. To them, I’m their friend/guardian. To me, they’re sisters who I can depend on.

I never thought of working in Korea after graduation. All I’ve been thinking about was working abroad, country after country, by myself.  Now i’m considering going back just so I can see them more often. One of my future goals is to take them on trips with the money I earned. I also aim to contribute to their college tuition fee. But I do hope they get scholarship.

Now i’m considering going back just so I can see them more often. One of my future goals is to take them on trips, just the three of us, with the money I earned. I also aim to contribute to their college tuition fee. But I do hope they get scholarship.

4/22/18, 10:54 AM - Julia Kang: S=1000      #number of simulation
betahat_ols=matrix(0,S,1)
for (s in 1:S){
  eu=mvrnorm(n,mu,Sigma)           
  e=eu[,1]
  u=eu[,2]
  z=rgamma(n,5)              
  x=z*gamma0+u             
  y=x*beta0+e              
  #betahat_ols[s]=sum(x*y)/sum(x*x)
  betahat_ols[s]=solve(x%*%x)*(x%*%y)  #matrix formula
}
hist(betahat_ols,main="Bias of OLS",xlab=expression(hat(beta)[ols]))
abline(v=mean(betahat_ols),col=4)
abline(v=beta0,col=2)
